Benson explained that he had a bumper harvest of watermelons and decided to give some to his cow, which unfortunately got sick later.
It was vomiting, according to him, and discharging water from the mouth. He wondered what could have been happening to his animal.
He asked if the watermelons could have caused the problem. “Is there any treatment I can give?” he concluded.
That was an interesting case. Watermelons are rarely fed to cattle in Kenya because they are highly in demand by humans and they are also not widely grown.





That said, they are not suitable to feed livestock because their water content – at 92 per cent – is extremely high. I have never seen a case of watermelon poisoning in ruminants. However, I remember seeing cases of pineapple and banana poisoning.
In science, we always look for precedents when faced with unfamiliar cases. I did some desk research but could not find any published material on watermelon poisoning in cattle.
I found an experimental case of the response of sheep fed watermelons for the first time. The sheep developed an illness called lactic acidosis whose severity directly depended on the quantity of watermelon consumed.
Gas and fluid accumulation
The sheep started showing signs of disease three hours after consuming the watermelons and became most ill after six hours. Signs of illness cleared within 12 to 24 hours if no more watermelons were fed.



