The signs of illness included poor appetite, dehydration, diarrhoea, depression and enlarged abdomen. There was also an increased heart rate.
The results of the study agreed with some of the signs Benson had seen in his cow. They also corresponded to what I thought was happening to the animal. I concluded the cow was suffering from lactic acidosis caused by the consumption of a large quantity of watermelons for the first time.
Since I could not tell how much watermelon the cow had eaten, I advised Benson to stop offering anymore and call in a veterinary doctor nearest to him.
The doctor would do physical examination of the animal and decide if the cow could recover on its own or it needed treatment.
Meanwhile, if the farmer had access to magnesium hydroxide, he could buy 500g and give the cow in water while waiting for the doctor. The chemical would work to neutralise the lactic acid in the cow’s stomach.
Sheep, cattle and goats are all ruminants and have a similar sickening way of handling large intakes of sugar or sugary feeds.
Therefore, feeds with high sugar content such as watermelons and other fruits should be introduced in small quantities, below 25 percent of the daily dry matter intake.



