This enables the rumen to adjust the type of micro-organisms required to break down lactic acid and prevent it from accumulating to toxic levels.
Ruminants, unlike other animals, do not vomit. What Benson had seen was escape of fluid due to the pressure exerted in the rumen by the gas and fluid accumulated in the organ. In some cases, the escaping fluid may enter the airways and cause death when it gets into the lungs.
Large amounts of water
Animals with lactic acidosis should be immediately stopped from feeding on the offending material. Water should also be withdrawn and they are put on dry grass such as hay. They should be kept in a cool shelter to minimise water loss from the body.
Moderate cases of lactic acidosis recover without treatment within 12 to 24 hours once the offending feed is withdrawn.
Such cases have some appetite for dry grass and do not show signs of dehydration such as dry muzzle and sunken eyes, extreme depression, and a progressively swelling abdomen.
Severe cases should be treated by a veterinary doctor. Antibiotics and anti-inflammatories are injected to prevent bacterial infection and minimise destruction of the rumen wall by lactic acid.
To neutralise blood acidity, a sterile solution of sodium bicarbonate should be injected into the bloodstream.



